name: (1E)-N-hydroxy-1-(4,7,7-trimethylbicyclo[2.2.1]hept-2-yl)propan-1-imine
source: Karthikeyan M.; Glen R.C.; Bender A. General melting point prediction based on a diverse compound dataset and artificial neural networks. J. Chem. Inf. Model.; 2005; 45(3); 581-878
Reason: 1,1'-Bis(methylene)propane, also known as cyclopentane, has a melting point of 100.5°C (according to the CRC Handbook of Chemistry and Physics, 49th Edition, 1968-1969). The compound we are analyzing has a hydroxyl group, which can increase the melting point due to increased molecular weight and hydrogen bonding potential. The methyl groups in the propane chain can also contribute to the melting point due to their increased molecular weight and rigidity. The cyclohexane ring in the structure can also contribute to the melting point due to its increased molecular weight and rigidity. The presence of a nitrogen atom in the structure can also increase the melting point due to increased molecular weight and the potential for hydrogen bonding.
